If you are able, please let me know how your network runs after you get everything set up, because I may have the same problem soon.  Thanks. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><img src= "http://home.earthlink.net/~asercion/tirsigns.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uzwitterion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zwitterion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/31/01 6:32:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13654.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Network/Cable question</span><hr size=1> I have an old junk PC running Win2K Pro with 2 NICs and Internet Connection Sharing.  <br>
<br>
It is just the box sitting there with no monitor, keyboard, or mouse.  I changed the startup profile for mouse and keyboard to be manual rather than automatic so that I didnt get that annoying &quot;some services failed to start&quot; message.<br>
<br>
The &quot;external&quot; NIC is connected directly to the broadband device via a crossover cable, this is the NIC with the IP address on the ISP's network.<br>
<br>
The &quot;internal&quot; NIC's IP is in the 192.168.xxx.xxx reserved range.  It is pluged into an ElCheapo $30 5-port hub.<br>
<br>
I have 3 other PCs on the network (the ones that I actually use) are all addressed in the 192.168.xxx.xxx range and have a gateway that is equal to the address of the &quot;internal&quot; NIC of the Win2K box.<br>
<br>
Each of the 3 PCs that I actually use has a different OS (Win95b, Win98 SE, &amp; WinME) so I don't think you'll have compatibility problems if you try this arrangement with any 32bit Windows machines.<br>
<br>
<br>
