<br>
<br>
Suppose you spent $400 on a an ISDN router when you could have spent $120 for a simple bridge.<br>
<br>
Suppose two years later you want to switch to ADSL because it is both cheaper and faster.<br>
<br>
Q: Where is that ISDN router going?<br>
A: Trash can<br>
<br>
<br>
Q: What if I had used the bridge with an old PC as router?<br>
A: You'd have saved $280 and you could STILL use your PC the exact same way with the new ADSL equipment. <br>
<br>
Q: Did the ISDN standard change? <br>
A: No.  The protocol is still the same.<br>
<br>
<br>
Q: Did the consumer STANDARD for high end internet change?<br>
A. Yes!  Almost nobody uses ISDN these days because ADSL and Cable Modems offer more bang for the buck.<br>
<br>
<br>
Q: Will my ISDN router still work?<br>
A: Yes.  Unless your phone company replaced all its switches (most of them did) and your router only works with the old ones.  Perhaps you can get a firmware flash... unless the company that made your router went belly up or was acquired/absorbed into another company.<br>
<br>
<br>
Q. Will I want to toss my ADSL bridge/router/firewall in the trash by 2005?<br>
A. Probably.  Something better will likely come along.<br>
<br>
